Trump and the Economy
New York—The financial markets finally woke up, realizing that Trump was the President of the United States.
The world has endured two years of unfiltered tweets and public statements from the most powerful person in the world, and the obvious question is, what has kept this going for so long?
On the one hand, up to now, investors have been treating Trump as a storm in the clouds with no rain.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies favorable to the corporate sector and shareholders, they will be willing to grant him the benefit of the doubt.
Many believe that in the end, "the adult in the room" will rein in Trump and ensure government policies remain within bounds.
Such assumptions were largely confirmed during the first year of Trump's presidency, a period when economic growth and expected corporate profit increases—due to the upcoming tax cuts and deregulation—boosted stock market performance.
In 2017, U.S. stock indices rose by more than 20 percent.
But in 2018, the situation took a sharp turn for the worse, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits rose by more than 20 percent (thanks to tax cuts), the U.S. stock market fluctuated up and down for most of the year and then plunged sharply.
Currently, various indices are in a correction range (i.e., down 10% from their most recent high), and technology stock indices (such as the Nasdaq) have fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although the increased volatility in financial markets reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other eurozone economies, as well as key emerging markets, the recent turbulence is due to Trump.
At the start of this year, Trump implemented reckless tax cuts, which pushed up long-term interest rates and drove the economy, already near full employment, to a peak.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first risk-averse surge of 2018.
Subsequently, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important U.S. trade partners.
Market concerns over protectionist policies of the government have fluctuated throughout the year but are now reaching new heights.
The U.S. recent moves against China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical cold war.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies may lead to stagflation (weakened growth and increased inflation).
Nevertheless, Trump's intention to restrict foreign direct investment inflows and implement broad immigration restrictions will hinder the growth of labor supply in the context of increasingly severe aging population and skill mismatches.
In addition, the Trump administration has yet to propose an infrastructure plan to stimulate private-sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy.
On Twitter and other occasions, Trump has continually criticized corporations' hiring, production, investment, and pricing behaviors, especially technology companies, which have already faced widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
Emerging markets were also impacted by U.S. policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening raised both short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the dollar.
As a result, emerging economies experienced capital outflows and rising values of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies that heavily rely on exports suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's energy policy created volatility.
The United States reimposing sanctions on Iran raised oil prices, and afterward, the U.S. government revoked exemptions and pressured Saudi Arabia to increase oil production, leading to a sharp drop in oil prices.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of U.S. energy companies could not hold up.
In addition, excessive volatility in oil prices is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders informed investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, now it is evident that nearly all the benefits from last year's tax cuts have flowed to the corporate sector rather than to households in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages.
This implies that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the primary cause of the recent quarter's sharp decline in both U.S. and global stock markets was Trump's own rhetoric and actions.
Worse still, Trump's open criticism of the Federal Reserve posed a more prominent risk than the outbreak of a full-scale trade war with China (despite his recent "truce" with Chinese President Xi Jinping). His attacks on the Federal Reserve began in the spring of 2018, when the U.S. economic growth rate exceeded 4 percent.
Due to these earlier attacks, the markets became skittish when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month and simultaneously signaled that rate hikes would proceed more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance was a response to Trump's attacks on it.
Faced with the hostile tweets from the president, Federal Reserve Chair Jerome Powell needed to send a signal that the central bank still maintains political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to fund his useless border wall with Mexico, Trump decided to shut down part of the federal government.
This move put the market into a state of near panic, and soon reports emerged that Trump wanted to fire Powell — which could turn the market correction into a crash.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to make a public statement to calm the markets.
He claimed that Trump had no intention of firing Powell, and that the U.S. fiscal situation was sound, which恰恰 highlighted the question of whether the situation was truly sound.
And recent personnel changes within the government, which may not directly affect economic decisions, have also caused market concerns.
The White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Defense Secretary James Mattis are set to leave, leaving the Trump administration with no sane individuals left.
The remaining will all be economic nationalists and foreign policy hawks who will follow Trump's lead.
At present, the possibility of all-out geopolitical conflict with China remains unresolved.
A new Cold War is likely to lead to deglobalization and disrupt global supply chains, but the technology sector will be hit first, as evidenced by recent cases involving ZTE and Huawei.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the cohesion of the EU and NATO during a period of economic and political instability in Europe.
The special prosecutor Robert Mueller's investigation into the relationship between Trump's 2016 campaign and Russia has been the sword of Damocles hanging over Trump's presidency.
Trump is now the Doctor Strangelove of financial markets.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a mutually assured economic destruction.
Now, the market has recognized this danger, with the risks of financial crisis and global recession rising steadily.
